{\b\fs26 6. Email Provenance Verification}
\par\par

{\b\fs22 What We Can Prove About an Email Wallet}
\par\par

{\b\fs20 6.1 Content Integrity Proofs}
\par\par

{\b Cryptographic Content Verification}
\par
{\f1\fs20 Provable Facts:
✓ Content has not been modified since wallet creation
✓ Exact timestamp of email processing
✓ Original email headers and metadata
✓ Complete attachment inventory and integrity
✓ IPFS storage location and retrieval hash}
\f0\fs24
\par\par

{\b Mathematical Proof Structure:}
\par
• {\b Hash Function Property:} SHA-256(content) → unique 256-bit fingerprint\par
• {\b Collision Resistance:} Computationally impossible to find different content with same hash\par
• {\b Blockchain Immutability:} Hash stored permanently with timestamp\par
• {\b Verification Process:} Re-hash current content, compare with stored hash\par\par

{\b\fs20 6.2 Ownership and Authorization Proofs}
\par\par

{\b Wallet Ownership Chain}
\par
{\f1\fs20 Ownership Provenance:
✓ Original email recipient wallet address
✓ Cryptographic signature proving authorization intent
✓ Blockchain transaction showing ownership transfer
✓ Current owner wallet address
✓ Complete ownership history with timestamps}
\f0\fs24
\par\par

{\b Authorization Verification:}
\par
• {\b Signature Verification:} Proves wallet owner authorized wallet creation\par
• {\b Message Authentication:} Specific authorization message signed\par
• {\b Non-Repudiation:} Signer cannot deny authorization\par
• {\b Timestamp Proof:} Exact time of authorization recorded\par\par

{\b\fs20 6.3 Service Processing Proofs}
\par\par

{\b Email Processing Verification}
\par
{\f1\fs20 Service Operation Proofs:
✓ Email received by monitored account (Microsoft Graph API logs)
✓ Content extraction performed by verified service
✓ Hash generation process auditable
✓ IPFS upload transaction recorded
✓ Blockchain transaction initiated by service wallet}
\f0\fs24
\par\par

{\b Service Integrity Chain:}
\par
• {\b Service Identity:} Known service wallet address with proven ownership\par
• {\b Operation Logging:} Complete audit trail of service operations\par
• {\b Transaction Verification:} All blockchain operations traceable\par
• {\b Process Transparency:} Open source processing algorithms\par\par

{\b\fs20 6.4 Temporal Proofs}
\par\par

{\b Time-Based Verification}
\par
{\f1\fs20 Temporal Provenance:
✓ Email reception timestamp (email headers)
✓ Processing timestamp (service logs)
✓ IPFS upload timestamp
✓ Blockchain transaction timestamp
✓ Authorization timestamp (user signature)}
\f0\fs24
\par\par

{\b Timeline Integrity:}
\par
• {\b Email Headers:} Original timestamp from email system\par
• {\b Service Processing:} Logged processing time\par
• {\b Blockchain Time:} Block timestamp (immutable)\par
• {\b Sequence Verification:} Logical order of operations\par\par

{\b\fs22 What We Cannot Prove}
\par\par

{\b Limitations and Scope}
\par
{\f1\fs20 Cannot Prove:
✗ Email authenticity before reaching monitored account
✗ Sender identity verification (requires separate email authentication)
✗ Email content truthfulness or accuracy
✗ Compliance with regulations in sender's jurisdiction
✗ Original composition device or location}
\f0\fs24
\par\par

{\b Email System Dependencies:}
\par
• {\b Email Authentication:} Relies on email provider's authentication (SPF, DKIM, DMARC)\par
• {\b Sender Verification:} Outside scope - email spoofing possible\par
• {\b Content Truthfulness:} System verifies integrity, not accuracy\par
• {\b Jurisdictional Compliance:} Cannot verify sender's legal compliance\par\par

{\b\fs22 Verification API}
\par\par

{\b Proof Generation Endpoints}
\par
